T1  - Moral Hazard in Corporate Investment and the Disciplinary Role of Voluntary Capital Rationing
AU  - Zhang, Guochang
Y1  - 1997/06/01
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/06/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.43.6.737
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.43.6.737
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 737
EP  - 750
VL  - 43
IS  - 6
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - This paper compares three capital-budgeting rules, the NPV rule, a high hurdle rate and capital rationing, and explains why some firms may voluntarily impose capital rationing. Under both capital rationing and a high hurdle, a restrictive investment criterion is used to control managerial shirking. However, implementation of these budgeting rules requires a mechanism to prevent the firm from expanding the investment scale ex post. Capital rationing, in the form of a predetermined, fixed budget, differs from the high-hurdle-rate rule in that the former requires the firm to overcome the cost of raising additional capital before making further investment.
AB  - This paper compares three capital-budgeting rules, the NPV rule, a high hurdle rate and capital rationing, and explains why some firms may voluntarily impose capital rationing. Under both capital rationing and a high hurdle, a restrictive investment criterion is used to control managerial shirking. However, implementation of these budgeting rules requires a mechanism to prevent the firm from expanding the investment scale ex post. Capital rationing, in the form of a predetermined, fixed budget, differs from the high-hurdle-rate rule in that the former requires the firm to overcome the cost of raising additional capital before making further investment.
